<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> The End<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 6, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> *NOTE: This article is pre-Mines of Moria*<br />
<br />
This Is The End.<br />
My Only Friend,<br />
The End.<br />
-The Doors<br />
<br />
The final dash from site six onwards is the most grueling couple of turns in Lord of the Rings. You no longer have a sanctuary to look forward to -- wounds on your characters (with the exception of many cards) are there to stay. No minion roams any more and rangers begin to show off their versatility. With the twilight pool high and draw decks slowly dwindling, a deck&#8217;s true colors will show. For both the shadow and fellowship players, this is when you get it on&#8230;<br />
<br />
Before breaking up this article into the fellowship and shadow points of views, its important to figure out what your primary objective from site seven through nine is going to be: overwhelm or corrupt Frodo or to get to site nine before your opponent does? These final couple of turns is where your shadow side will truly have to compliment your fellowship side or vice versa. As for how to play each side&#8230;:<br />
<br />
FELLOWSHIP:<br />
<br />
Working as a fellowship player who&#8217;s goal is to reach site nine, one of the most important things to remember is save your exertion. Yes, using Aragorn and Bow at site eight may stop you from having to skirmish Lurtz, but losing a companion in that skirmish may be much more useful then having to face that same threat, but with an additional minion, at site nine. Another great example is Albert Dreary: canceling that Saruman&#8217;s Snows may save you early on, but if you suddenly find yourself being unable to use Bounder at site nine, though luck&#8230;<br />
<br />
Don&#8217;t waste companions until you reach site nine. In the similar vein of only exerting when nessceary, companions and allies like Pippin and Tharin becomes gold at site nine. The sudden ability to lose nothing but a card that your suppose to lose at site nine can you free up against swarms. <br />
<br />
Pack down at site six: don&#8217;t ad nessceary twilight. The sites that they&#8217;re giving off and your companionship is already plenty for almost all shadow decks -- adding companions, possessions that late in the game can be devastating, allowing the Uruk-Hai and Nazgul to get out a third or fourth minion at any site can be game. Only play cards that will directly be key in losing or winning (such as Albert Dreary or Legolas, Greenleaf). Sure, Gwemegil is useful in a skirmish, but the two twilight it adds could be the difference in letting an above-surface Cave Troll come out at site nine. The simple fact is don&#8217;t play things if you don&#8217;t need them and twilight denial (such as No Stranger To The Shadows) is instrumental in a site nine victory.<br />
<br />
When trying to race to site nine, your shadow half should have a fairly cut-and-dry concept: don&#8217;t let them beat you. This translates to basically making it fairly unfathomable for them to want to make a double move. While you may not necessarily kill anyone, a Troop of Uruk-Hai with Uruk-Hai Rampage or a Nazgul in any form will make a player think twice about taking the another move. If you plan to run a fast companionship, make sure to splash in the likes of some Uruk-Hai and Spies of Saruman because A Ranger&#8217;s Versatility and archery can be deadly if your not prepared for it at sites seven and eight. Other ways to make that double move unlikely is to run Sauron (since they&#8217;ll finally stop roaming) and a bunch of Under The Watching Eyes. The constant exertion will allow you to slow wear down the fellowship, causing a late game double move to look less and less attractive. <br />
<br />
SHADOW:<br />
<br />
If your goal is to overwhelm (or corrupt) the ring-bearer around site nine, your primary goal should be getting out minions and just knocking down the ranks of the fellowship until you finally hit Frodo. This doesn&#8217;t have to be Moria, either; fierce Nazgul, damage +1 Uruk-Hai, and exert-to-wound Sauron Orc and all the tricks each culture has can do the same thing. There&#8217;s really two schools of thought here concerning how to reach ol&#8216; Frodo: 1) Old Fashioned Beat Down and 2) The Last Turn Push.<br />
<br />
The Beat Down is pretty straight forward: just do what most decks already do at sites two through six and play minions and conditions in hopes of just causing damage, adding burdens, or whatever your deck&#8217;s primary strategy is. Take advantage of the higher twilight pool and the devastating game texts on the site and simply run with it. Fierceness and damage +1 minions will help in this task: with no sanctuary during the last haul, its fairly feasible to kill off the companionship in time to reach Frodo by the time your fighting at site nine.<br />
<br />
However, there&#8217;s risks to this. If it fails and your at site nine with only a couple minions, your out of the game. The other option that presents itself is a Last Turn Push. The basic concept here is go light on minions between sites seven and nine, basically only playing ones that are guaranteed to take out something (and with A Ranger&#8217;s Versatility, that&#8217;s not much). At site nine, you swarm them. Of course, Moria is built for this, but Sauron can also do this with precise devastation at Tol Brandir. However, why leave our Nazguls and Uruk-Hai friends out? If the twilight pools big enough (or the Morgul Gates are in hand), it&#8217;s still feasible to get a few of these baddies out, enough to wear down the ranks of the fellowship and allow their fierceness to beat up on Frodo.<br />
<br />
Both of the above schools of thinking for the shadow have risks, however, both of them rely on their fellowship for one simple thing: drawing cards. Basically, that half of your deck which is fellowship has to be discarded or played as soon as possible as of to allow more shadow cards to be drawn. If your going for the beat down at site nine, use They Are Coming. It fits into any deck, even if not using Moria, simply because it lets you modulate your hand draw what you need when you need it.<br />
<br />
SITES:<br />
<br />
For either the fellowship or shadow, sites are going to make the difference during the final push. Site nine itself can be game ending: Tol Brandir can pull a swarm from discard alone and Emyn Muil or Slopes of Amon Hen are meant for the Uruk-Hai. Facing your opponent&#8217;s sites (especially ones like Anduin Wilderland can be devastating). I can&#8217;t stress the importance of Thor&#8217;s Map, Pathfinder, and Ularie Neyla: the ability to control the adventure one is powerful. For instance, there is only one site nine, Tol Brandir. If your running Versatility, this can be the key to victory, but if your opponent isn&#8217;t playing Sauron, you&#8217;ll never see it unless you run it for them by using the Map or Pathfinder. <br />
<br />
In conclusion, the most intense turns of a Lord of the Rings game are the last few. How you play them, either shadow or fellowship, should be reflected by the rest of your deck and not simply a jumble of powerful cards that have no connection to each other. A Lord of the Rings deck is like a tapestry and each card should be interwoven with the next to provide of the maximum strength. This is what makes a deck a consistent winner, when each card in it has a purpose and is not just in there because it&#8217;s the next fad card.<br />
<br />
Don&#8217;t get lost on the path,<br />
<br />
-Drew<br />
